Diagnosis.
D. hypocrita
can be distinguished from all other species of the genus by the combination of the following characters: the shape of the superior prong of the RTA, abruptly rising from the tibia and then straight to the narrowed tip ( Figs 5, 9 ), the long and styliform tip of the coil (
Figs 4 –5, 8– 9
), the huge basal tubercle of the terminal apophysis projecting forward (
Figs 8–9
), the finger-shaped membranous coils and the singular shape of the distal part of the coiled ducts ( Figs 3, 7 ), often easily visible through the abdominal tegument (
Fig. 6
).
